> Food can be a great opportunity for increasing your vocabulary and nowhere is this more apparent than with the word 'schnitzel'. We conjured up a thousand ideas on what this word could mean, though it turns out it simply means 'cut' (as in a 'cut' of meat). The schnitzel also happens to be a close cousin of the escalope, the milanese and the milanesa in case you need to order it abroad!

Boil a large #pot{} of water with a @salt{pinch} for the potatoes. Wash the @New Potatoes{1} (but keep the nutritious skins on). Cut your potatoes into quarters. Cook in the boiling water for ~{10-15%minutes}, until cooked through.

Put the @Panko Breadcrumbs{1} in a big #bowl{} with a @salt{pinch} and a few good grinds of @black pepper{a few good grinds}. Coat each @Pork Medallion{2} evenly in the @Sour Cream{2}, then press each medallion into the breadcrumbs until completely coated. 

> You've now made pork schnitzels!

Heat a splash of @Olive Oil{1} in a large #frying pan{}. Lay your pork in the pan and cook for ~{4-5%minutes} on each side.

> Cook these in batches to make sure the pan retains its heat and gives a lovely golden colour to the schnitzels. The pork is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Drain your potatoes when they're done and rinse them under cold water for ~{1%minute}.

> This will stop them from cooking further and cool them slightly for your warm potato salad.

In a bowl, use a #fork{} to whisk together the @Dijon Mustard{1}, @Balsamic Vinegar{1/3} and @Olive Oil{1} with a small pinch of @salt{small pinch} and @black pepper{small pinch}.

> To sweeten the dressing, you can add a pinch of sugar if you have any.

Toss the @Wild Rocket{1} and your slightly cooled potatoes in the dressing. Halve the @Black Olives{1} and scatter them on top.

Serve your schnitzels on your potato salad and sprinkle over some @Lemon{1/2}(zested).